=E2=80=9COne of your employees has said that you collect half a gigabyte, w=
hatever that is, of information on your customers every day. That=E2=80=99s=
 about 350 floppy disks=E2=80=99 worth. What do you do with that informatio=
n?!=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CIs this investing or is it gambling?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CRight now w=
ith the frenzy we=E2=80=99ve had, right now it feels more like gambling.=E2=
=80=9D
See what I mean?=C2=A0
Now, I admit that there=E2=80=99s survivorship bias here. I could probably =
go back and find 60 Minutes features on companies that seemed crazy and end=
ed up failing. Amazon=E2=80=99s ultimate success doesn=E2=80=99t necessaril=
y mean that crypto will succeed. But the similarity in the tone towards Ama=
zon then and the tone towards crypto today is eerie: this is big, and we do=
n=E2=80=99t understand why it=E2=80=99s so big, so let=E2=80=99s cover it, =
laugh it off, and move on.
